<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="159" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,150,1149]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,654,680]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Heffern &amp; Santos-Silva, 2022" authorityName="Heffern &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2022" box="[323,485,654,680]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="raberi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[323,485,654,680]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Juninia raberi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[493,584,654,680]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[493,584,654,680]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is provisionally included in this genus, awaiting the discovery of the male. It differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirsch" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[317,461,690,716]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulifera">
<emphasis box="[317,461,690,716]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">J. annulifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[476,604,690,716]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–17" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1814,1838]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1789]" captionTargetId="figure-29@4.[151,1436,181,1790]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 13–17. Juninia annulifera (Kirsch, 1889). 13–16) Juninia leechi Lane, 1966, paratype male: 13) Dorsal habitus; 14) Ventral habitus; 15) Lateral habitus; 16) Elytral carinae. 17) Female, dorsal habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6581640" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6581640/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Figs 13–17</figureCitation>
) as follows: posterior area of vertex and area behind upper eye lobes with dense white pubescent macula (absent in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirsch" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[624,769,726,752]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulifera">
<emphasis box="[624,769,726,752]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">J. annulifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); central area of the pronotum and most of the elytra with minute yellowish pubescence (yellowish-white on the pronotum and grayish-white on the elytra, both distinctly more conspicuous in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirsch" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[390,533,798,824]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulifera">
<emphasis box="[390,533,798,824]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">J. annulifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); pronotum with two dense white pubescent maculae on each side (with a single macula from base to apex in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirsch" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[477,621,834,860]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulifera">
<emphasis box="[477,621,834,860]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">J. annulifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); elytra with semicircular white pubescent macula close to the suture on posterior third (absent in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirsch" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[442,588,870,896]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulifera">
<emphasis box="[442,588,870,896]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">J. annulifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); lateral carina (
<figureCitation box="[778,862,870,897]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–38" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1593,1617]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1569]" captionTargetId="figure-22@9.[151,1436,181,1569]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 33–38. Juninia raberi sp. nov. 33–37) Holotype female: 33) Dorsal habitus; 34) Ventral habitus; 35) Lateral habitus; 36) Elytral carinae; 37) Head, frontal view. 38) Paratype female, dorsal habitus (by Armando Ruiz Boyer)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6581650" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6581650/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
) placed close to the humeral carina from the base (not close to the humeral carina (
<figureCitation box="[525,608,906,933]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–17" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1814,1838]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1789]" captionTargetId="figure-29@4.[151,1436,181,1790]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 13–17. Juninia annulifera (Kirsch, 1889). 13–16) Juninia leechi Lane, 1966, paratype male: 13) Dorsal habitus; 14) Ventral habitus; 15) Lateral habitus; 16) Elytral carinae. 17) Female, dorsal habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6581640" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6581640/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kirsch" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[653,798,906,932]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulifera">
<emphasis box="[653,798,906,932]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">J. annulifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Additionally, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Heffern &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2022" box="[974,1136,906,932]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Juninia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="raberi">
<emphasis box="[974,1136,906,932]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Juninia raberi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the female of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" baseAuthorityYear="1992" box="[151,383,942,968]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Sibapipunga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beckeri">
<emphasis box="[151,383,942,968]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Sibapipunga beckeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[400,530,942,969]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–26" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1920,1944]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,382,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-136@6.[151,1436,381,1897]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 21–26. Sibapipunga beckeri (Martins &amp; Galileo, 1992). 21) Holotype female, dorsal habitus. 22–25) Male: 22) Dorsal habitus; 23) Ventral habitus; 24) Lateral habitus; 25) Frontal tubercles. 26) Holotype female, elytral carinae (by Diego de Santana Souza)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6581646" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6581646/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Figs 21–26</figureCitation>
) by the longer antennae, elytra with semicircular white pubescent macula close to the suture on the posterior third (absent in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" baseAuthorityYear="1992" box="[680,793,978,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Sibapipunga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beckeri">
<emphasis box="[680,793,978,1005]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">S. beckeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and tarsomeres III proportionally smaller (larger in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" baseAuthorityYear="1992" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Sibapipunga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beckeri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">S. beckeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); it differs from females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1956" box="[550,737,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Purusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acreana">
<emphasis box="[550,737,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Purusia acreana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[752,879,1014,1040]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–12. 1–8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1902,1926]" captionTargetBox="[201,1386,181,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-22@3.[201,1386,181,1878]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–12. 1–8) Purusia acreana Lane, 1956, holotype male: 1) Dorsal habitus; 2) Ventral habitus; 3) Lateral habitus; 4) Elytral carinae; 5) Head, frontal view; 6) Head, lateral view; 7) Scape, apical cicatrix; 8) Scape, detail. 9–11) Purusia acreana, female: 9) Head, lateral view; 10) Dorsal habitus; 11) Ventral habitus. 12) Purusiella wappesi (Martins &amp; Galileo, 2004), scape. Figure 12 by Francisco Eriberto de Lima Nascimento (MZSP)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6581638" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6581638/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Figs 10–11</figureCitation>
) by the body proportionally stouter (slender in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1956" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Purusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acreana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">P. acreana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), spiniform projection of the outer elytral apex distinctly shorter (longer in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1956" box="[1092,1211,1051,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Purusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acreana">
<emphasis box="[1092,1211,1051,1076]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">P. acreana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), pronotum without dense white pubescent macula on center of posterior region (present in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1956" box="[958,1077,1087,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Purusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acreana">
<emphasis box="[958,1077,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">P. acreana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and pronotum with two dense white pubescent maculae on each side (with a single macula from base to apex in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1956" box="[1068,1186,1123,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Purusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acreana">
<emphasis box="[1068,1186,1123,1148]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">P. acreana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
